---
// src/pages/press/index.astro
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  door="press"
  title="The Missing Story"
  description="The professional labor market has a structural compensation problem that collective bargaining theory predicts and empirical evidence confirms. The skinny union is the mechanism that solves it."
>

  <!-- ── Door Hero — Sober Register ────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="door-hero door-hero--press" aria-label="Press door">
      <p class="door-hero-eyebrow">Press</p>
      <h1 class="door-hero-headline">
        The <em>missing story</em> in American labor.
      </h1>
      <div class="door-hero-rule"></div>
      <p class="door-hero-sub">
        The legal architecture exists. The labor market analysis is documented. The workers
        are there. The union has not been built — until now.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── The Legal Foundation Line ────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <div class="licensed-break licensed-break--cobalt">
      <p>
        The skinny union rests on a legal foundation that is sound under existing law and
        does not depend on any court adopting a new rule.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── The Labor Market Argument ────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="The labor market argument">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Analysis I</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">The Labor Market Argument</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>The professional worker who has concluded that unions are not for her is probably right — about the unions she has seen.</h2>

        <p>
          The perception that collective bargaining comes bundled with organizational rigidity,
          bureaucratic hierarchy, and a structural commitment to protecting members from the
          consequences of poor performance is not an ideological bias. It is an accurate
          description of what most existing union models deliver. The question is whether it
          applies to this one.
        </p>

        <p>
          It does not.
        </p>

        <p>
          Professional workers operating in places where employment law already does substantial
          protective work are not well-served by a union model built for workers who needed a
          union to do that work. What those workers have not been offered is a union that
          concentrates entirely on compensation — wages set by negotiation rather than by what
          the individual market will bear when one person bargains alone against an institution
          with years of data on exactly what each worker will accept.
        </p>

        <p>
          The skinny union makes one correction to that arrangement. Wages become a subject for
          collective negotiation. Everything else — performance management, discipline, at-will
          employment, restructuring decisions — operates exactly as it would without a union in
          place.
        </p>

        <blockquote class="pull-quote">
          The employer is negotiating with a group whose coordinated exit, were it exercised,
          would be costly in a way that any individual's departure is not.
        </blockquote>

        <p>
          That is the only correction the model makes. For the professional worker whose primary
          concern is compensation and whose employment relationship is otherwise working, it is a
          precisely calibrated tool — not the instrument a different generation of workers built
          for a different problem, but one designed for the problem she actually has.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Why Unions Don't Reach You ───────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Why unions don't reach professional workers">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Analysis II</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Why Unions Don't Reach You</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>Worker organizations take the shape of their most motivated members.</h2>

        <p>
          If you've looked at what unions actually do and concluded they weren't designed for
          you, you were right. That's not cynicism. It's an accurate reading of how institutions
          work, and what happens when workers with a specific, urgent problem organize around it.
        </p>

        <p>
          The members who feel the sharpest, most immediate threat to their economic lives are
          the ones who organize hardest, stay most engaged, and drive bargaining priorities over
          time. They're in the room. They run for officer positions. They care intensely about
          the next contract. What the most motivated constituency cares about, the institution
          eventually fights for. That's not a failure — that's how collective institutions work.
        </p>

        <p>
          In the industries where traditional union structures took hold, the workers with the
          most acute reason to organize were workers who could be fired on a supervisor's
          say-so and had nowhere else to go. The institutions that formed around that problem
          built apparatus for that problem: discipline procedures, grievance machinery,
          arbitration rights. They built it well. The apparatus serves those workers.
        </p>

        <p>
          The professional worker whose employment is otherwise secure — who operates in a liquid
          job market, who would not trade any leverage on compensation for leverage on
          discipline — is not the worker those unions were built for. She has no organization
          that concentrates entirely on her most urgent concern. The Skinny Union is that
          organization.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Press Kit ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Press resources">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Resources</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Press Kit</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>For reporters and editors.</h2>
        <div class="placeholder">
          <span class="placeholder-label">Coming — Press Kit</span>
          <p>
            The advocacy publication (full argument), quotable framings, background on the legal
            architecture, and contact information. Available on request in the interim.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>
